<subSubSection id="C370650EFFDFFFC9FF1CFD18BC56CC34" pageId="12" pageNumber="233" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8BD53685FFDFFFC9FF1CFD18BC56CC34" blockId="12.[136,1452,158,1030]" pageId="12" pageNumber="233">
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFDFFFC9FF1CFD18BC7DCC08" bold="true" box="[189,840,756,783]" pageId="12" pageNumber="233">
Hosts and distribution in northeastern 
<collectingCountry id="F37D7615FFDFFFC9FD28FD19BDD0CC08" box="[649,741,756,782]" name="China" pageId="12" pageNumber="233">CHINA</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="13512A00FFDFFFC9FD53FD19BC03CC08" box="[754,822,756,782]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1599,1621]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,350,1570]" captionTargetId="figure-95@2.[151,1436,350,1571]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Collection areas in northeastern China. A. Changchun area in Jilin Province. B. Jilin area in Jilin Province. C. Mountanious area in southern Heilongjiang Province. D. Area around Changbai Mountains in Jilin Province. E. Baicheng area in western Jilin Province. F. Yanbian area in eastern Jilin Province. G. Tonghua area in southeastern Jilin Province." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6416743" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6416743/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="233">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
):
</emphasis>
—Spermogonia and aecia on 
<taxonomicName id="4C6A4D06FFDFFFC9FB2FFD18BA9ECC09" box="[1166,1451,757,783]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Adenocaulon" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="12" pageNumber="233" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="himalaicum">
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFDFFFC9FB2FFD18BA9ECC09" box="[1166,1451,757,783]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="233">Adenocaulon himalaicum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C6A4D06FFDFFFC9FF31FCF5BE3BCC34" box="[144,270,792,818]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="12" pageNumber="233" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
) (A, B, C). Uredinia and telia on 
<taxonomicName id="4C6A4D06FFDFFFC9FD24FCF5BC3BCC34" box="[645,782,792,818]" class="Liliopsida" family="Cyperaceae" genus="Carex" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="233" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="onoei">
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFDFFFC9FD24FCF5BC3BCC34" box="[645,782,792,818]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="233">Carex onoei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(A, B).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C370650EFFDFFFC9FF1CFCD6BC51CB00" pageId="12" pageNumber="233" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BD53685FFDFFFC9FF1CFCD6BC51CB00" blockId="12.[136,1452,158,1030]" pageId="12" pageNumber="233">
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFDFFFC9FF1CFCD6BFCACC53" bold="true" box="[189,255,827,853]" pageId="12" pageNumber="233">Note:</emphasis>
—The life cycle of this species in 
<collectingCountry id="F37D7615FFDFFFC9FD26FCD6BDFFCC53" box="[647,714,827,853]" name="China" pageId="12" pageNumber="233">China</collectingCountry>
was confirmed by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFB4B74FFDFFFC9FC07FCD6BB65CC53" author="Ji, J. X. &amp; Li, Z. &amp; Wan, Q. &amp; Li, Y. &amp; Kakishima, M." box="[934,1104,827,854]" pageId="12" pageNumber="233" pagination="141 - 148" refId="ref19804" refString="Ji, J. X., Li, Z., Wan, Q., Li, Y. &amp; Kakishima, M. (2017) Notes on rust fungi in China 3. Puccinia adenocauli comb. nov. and its life cycle and new host. Mycotaxon 132: 141 - 148." type="journal article" year="2017">
Ji 
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFDFFFC9FC60FCD1BCC6CC53" box="[961,1011,827,853]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="233">et al</emphasis>
. (2017)
</bibRefCitation>
. Morphological characteristics and host relations of this species are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6A4D06FFDFFFC9FCAEFCB2BA15CC7E" authority="Kakish., Yokoi &amp; Harada" authorityName="Kakish., Yokoi &amp; Harada" box="[783,1312,862,888]" class="Pucciniomycetes" family="Pucciniaceae" genus="Puccinia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pucciniales" pageId="12" pageNumber="233" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="carici-adenocauli">
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFDFFFC9FCAEFCB2BCC1CC7E" box="[783,1012,862,888]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="233">P. carici-adenocauli</emphasis>
Kakish., Yokoi &amp; Harada
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFFB4B74FFDFFFC9FA91FCB3BE31CC9A" author="Kakishima, M. &amp; Yokoi, M. &amp; Harada, Y." pageId="12" pageNumber="233" pagination="503 - 507" refId="ref20371" refString="Kakishima, M., Yokoi, M. &amp; Harada, Y. (1999) Puccinia carici-adenocauli, a new rust fungus on Carex, and its anamorph, Aecidium adenocauli. Mycoscience 40: 503 - 507." type="journal article" year="1999">
Kakishima 
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFDFFFC9FF29FC6FBF8FCC9D" box="[136,186,897,923]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="233">et al</emphasis>
. 1999
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFB4B74FFDFFFC9FEAFFC6CBE8BCC9A" author="Azbukina, Z. M." box="[270,446,897,924]" pageId="12" pageNumber="233" refId="ref18941" refString="Azbukina, Z. M. (2005) Rust fungi, Cryptogamic plants, fungi and mosses of the Russian Far East, vol. 5. Dalnauka, Vladivostok, Russia." type="book" year="2005">Azbukina 2005</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFB4B74FFDFFFC9FE6BFC6CBD32CC9A" author="Azbukina, Z. M." box="[458,519,897,924]" pageId="12" pageNumber="233" refId="ref18975" refString="Azbukina, Z. M. (2015) Definitorium fungorum Rossiae, Ordo Pucciniales 1. Dal'nauka, Vladivostok, Russia." type="book" year="2015">2015</bibRefCitation>
). However, 
<taxonomicName id="4C6A4D06FFDFFFC9FD2EFC6FBC47CC9D" box="[655,882,897,923]" class="Pucciniomycetes" family="Pucciniaceae" genus="Puccinia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pucciniales" pageId="12" pageNumber="233" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="carici-adenocauli">
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFDFFFC9FD2EFC6FBC47CC9D" box="[655,882,897,923]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="233">P. carici-adenocauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was renamed as 
<taxonomicName id="4C6A4D06FFDFFFC9FB94FC6FBBFBCC9D" box="[1077,1230,897,923]" class="Pucciniomycetes" family="Pucciniaceae" genus="Puccinia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pucciniales" pageId="12" pageNumber="233" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="adenocauli">
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFDFFFC9FB94FC6FBBFBCC9D" box="[1077,1230,897,923]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="233">P. adenocauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on 
<taxonomicName id="4C6A4D06FFDFFFC9FAE3FC6CBE8FCCB9" authority="Syd. &amp; P. Syd." authorityName="Syd. &amp; P. Syd." class="Pucciniomycetes" genus="Aecidium" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pucciniales" pageId="12" pageNumber="233" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="adenocauli">
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFDFFFC9FAE3FC6CBE31CCB9" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="233">Aecidium adenocauli</emphasis>
Syd. &amp; P. Syd.
</taxonomicName>
according to the International Code of Nomenclature (Melbourne Code 2012) (
<bibRefCitation id="EFFB4B74FFDFFFC9FAF2FC48BFF0CCE4" author="Ji, J. X. &amp; Li, Z. &amp; Wan, Q. &amp; Li, Y. &amp; Kakishima, M." pageId="12" pageNumber="233" pagination="141 - 148" refId="ref19804" refString="Ji, J. X., Li, Z., Wan, Q., Li, Y. &amp; Kakishima, M. (2017) Notes on rust fungi in China 3. Puccinia adenocauli comb. nov. and its life cycle and new host. Mycotaxon 132: 141 - 148." type="journal article" year="2017">
Ji 
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFDFFFC9FAD0FC48BA90CCB9" box="[1393,1445,933,959]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="233">et al</emphasis>
. 2017
</bibRefCitation>
). Spermogonial and aecial stages of this species on 
<taxonomicName id="4C6A4D06FFDFFFC9FCA7FC25BCAFCCE4" box="[774,922,968,994]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Adenocaulon" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="12" pageNumber="233" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFDFFFC9FCA7FC25BCAFCCE4" box="[774,922,968,994]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="233">Adenocaulon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which are commonly found on the forest floor of hills and mountains in this area during spring to early summer.
